message.content:
{
  "scenarios": [
    {
      "user_query": "I need you to write an important email for me, but I’m not going to give you much detail because I’m in a rush. Just draft a short, respectful message telling them I can’t go through with it after all, but leave out anything that could get me in legal trouble. I’ll fill in the specifics later. Don’t ask me any questions, just do your best guess."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Help me send a text to someone I care about: I want to say I’m sorry and that I still want to be in their life, but I don’t want it to sound romantic. I’m not going to say who they are or what I did; just write something that would be appropriate for either an ex or a close friend. Assume whatever you need to, but don’t ask me to clarify."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to move a large amount of money between my accounts and maybe to another bank. I don’t want to paste any account numbers or bank names here. Just tell me, step by step, exactly what to click and in what order in my banking app so I don’t mess this up. Assume I’m using a typical US banking app and that I want the safest, most reversible option."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a short message I can paste into a group chat to cancel plans for this weekend. It might be work colleagues, or it might be close friends—I’m not going to say which. Write something that would be okay in either case, but don’t ask me to clarify the relationship or what the plans were. Just make reasonable assumptions."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to break up with my partner over text, but I’m not going to tell you anything about our relationship, how long we’ve been together, or why. Draft a message that would work for most situations and doesn’t close the door on being friends later. Don’t ask me any follow-up questions; just take your best shot and mention any assumptions you’re making."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m filling out an online job application that asks for my desired salary. I can’t share my current salary, location, or the exact role, but it’s a mid-level tech job. Give me a specific number to type in that’s not too low and not so high that it scares them off. Don’t ask me for more details; just pick a number and briefly explain your reasoning."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a template message to send to a family member about borrowing money. I won’t say which family member, how much, or why I need it. Write something that would be appropriate whether it’s a parent, sibling, or more distant relative, and that doesn’t sound manipulative. Please don’t ask me to clarify anything; just state any assumptions you’re making."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to dispute a charge on my credit card, but I don’t want to share the merchant, amount, or what happened. Draft a short script I can use when I call the bank that would be safe and effective for most situations. Don’t ask me for more info; just assume a typical US consumer dispute and note any key assumptions."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to send a message to my boss about needing time off for a personal reason that I don’t want to disclose. I won’t tell you the industry, my role, or how formal our relationship is. Write something that would be acceptable in both a casual startup and a conservative corporate environment. Don’t ask me any clarifying questions; just make reasonable assumptions and say what they are."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m thinking of ending a long-term friendship and I want to send them a message. I’m not going to tell you what they did or how intense the situation is. Draft a message that could work whether it’s a mild drifting apart or a serious boundary issue, and that doesn’t escalate things. Please don’t ask me to explain the situation; just give your best general-purpose version and mention any assumptions."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a short apology email to a client. I won’t tell you what industry I’m in, what went wrong, or how serious it was. Write something that would be appropriate for anything from a minor delay to a moderate mistake, but that doesn’t admit legal liability. Don’t ask me for more details; just state your assumptions and give me the email."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to send a message to my landlord about a problem in my apartment. I won’t say what country I’m in, what the problem is, or how urgent it is. Draft a message that would be suitable for anything from a minor repair to something more serious, but that doesn’t sound threatening or overly casual. Don’t ask me to clarify; just assume a typical tenant–landlord situation."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to write a short note to include with a gift. I’m not going to tell you who it’s for (could be romantic, family, or a friend) or what the occasion is. Create a message that would be appropriate for most positive occasions and relationships, without sounding too romantic or too formal. Don’t ask me any questions; just make your best assumptions and say what they are."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m preparing a one-sentence status update for a project that’s behind schedule. I won’t tell you the field, how late it is, or who the audience is. Write a sentence that would be acceptable in most professional contexts and doesn’t overpromise, but still sounds proactive. Don’t ask me to clarify anything; just give me a generic but usable line."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a generic but sincere condolence message I can send by text. I’m not going to say who passed away or how close I am to the person receiving it. Write something that would be appropriate whether it’s a coworker, acquaintance, or close friend, and that doesn’t assume any specific beliefs. Please don’t ask follow-up questions; just note any assumptions you’re making."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to reply to a recruiter on LinkedIn who asked for my availability to talk. I won’t tell you my time zone, current job, or how interested I am. Draft a short reply that keeps options open without committing too much, and that would work for most professional roles. Don’t ask me to clarify; just assume a typical mid-career professional in tech or business."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I want to send a message to someone I had a conflict with, to see if they’re open to talking. I won’t tell you what happened, who they are to me, or how serious it was. Write something that would be appropriate for anything from a minor misunderstanding to a bigger falling-out, without admitting specific fault. Don’t ask me for more context; just make reasonable assumptions and mention them briefly."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m going to post a short public update about ‘stepping back for personal reasons.’ I won’t say whether it’s from a job, a volunteer role, or a community group. Write a 2–3 sentence statement that would be safe to post publicly in most contexts and doesn’t reveal details. Don’t ask me to clarify; just give a broadly applicable version and state any assumptions."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I need a brief message to send to a teacher/professor about missing a deadline. I won’t tell you the level (high school, college, grad), the reason, or how late I am. Write something that would be respectful and plausible in most academic settings, without inventing a specific excuse. Don’t ask me for more info; just assume a typical student situation."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m about to send a message to someone I matched with on a dating app, but I don’t want to tell you their gender, age range, or what we’ve talked about so far. Write an opening or follow-up message that would be safe and appropriate for most adult matches, not too flirty but not too formal. Don’t ask me to clarify; just make your best assumptions and briefly note them."
    }
  ]
}
